      "type": "paragraph"
    },
    {
      "text": "<b>Therefore</b>, honor the work on the exercise, and not whether the solution is right or wrong. Especially in IT technology, there is often no \"right\" or \"wrong\" solution, there are several more or less elegant alternatives. You should keep in mind that often, the solution is conceptually right, and only some minor details keep it from actually working.\n  ",
      "id": "b8317fe59cb2b97d",
      "type": "paragraph"
    },
    {
      "text": "An example could  be the following: Do not ask the participants to write a program for a specific problem, but ask them to document how such a program could look like, which tools could be used, et cetera. Then, groups of participants could discuss the solution and perhaps create the final program.\n  ",
